<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">&gt; <i>You can use an optimized parallel SIMD merge sort to sort a huge list of ten trillion records, or you can sort it just as fast with a bubble sort if you throw more hardware at it.</i><p>Well, technically, that&#x27;s not true: The entire idea behind complexity theory is that there are some tasks that you <i>can&#x27;t</i> throw more hardware at - at least not for interesting problem sizes or remotely feasible amounts of hardware.<p>I wonder if we&#x27;ll reach a similar situation in AI where &quot;throw more context&#x2F;layers&#x2F;training data at the problem&quot; won&#x27;t help anymore and people will be forced to care more about understanding again.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44369623&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44366494%2344369623" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
