<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">We can be sure via analysis based on computational theory, e.g. <a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;arxiv.org&#x2F;abs&#x2F;2503.03961" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;arxiv.org&#x2F;abs&#x2F;2503.03961</a> and <a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;arxiv.org&#x2F;abs&#x2F;2310.07923" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;arxiv.org&#x2F;abs&#x2F;2310.07923</a> . This lets us know what classes of problems a model is able to solve, and sufficiently deep transformers with chain of thought have been shown to be theoretically capable of solving a very large class of problems.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44367776&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44366494%2344367776" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
