<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">Keep in mind that proofs of transformers being able to solve all problems in some complexity class work by taking a known universal algorithm for that complexity class and encoding it as a transformer. In every such case, you&#x27;d be better off using the universal algorithm you started with in the first place.<p>Maybe the hope is that you won&#x27;t have to manually map the universal algorithm to your specific problem and can just train the transformer to figure it out instead, but there are few proofs that transformers can solve all problems in some complexity class through <i>training</i> instead of manual construction.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44369625&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44366494%2344369625" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
</table></td></tr><tr class="athing comtr" id="44367945"><td><table border="0">  <tr>    <td class='ind' indent='2'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="80"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks">
